Step 1 — Move the key into ~/.ssh with a clean (space-free) name
Filenames with spaces break ssh -i constantly. Copy it to a normal location:

mkdir -p ~/.ssh && chmod 700 ~/.ssh
cp "/Users/aubairakif/Codebases/PRMSC-HO/Work Force Management/Work Force Management"     ~/.ssh/wfm_instance
cp "/Users/aubairakif/Codebases/PRMSC-HO/Work Force Management/Work Force Management.pub" ~/.ssh/wfm_instance.pub
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/wfm_instance
chmod 644 ~/.ssh/wfm_instance.pub
Step 2 — Connect
A) If this key was added during instance creation (key auth already works):

ssh -i ~/.ssh/wfm_instance adminprms98@101.50.84.209
B) If it asks for a password or rejects the key, the public key isn't on the server yet. Install it once using the password you set at creation:

# macOS includes ssh-copy-id on recent versions:
ssh-copy-id -i ~/.ssh/wfm_instance.pub adminprms98@101.50.84.209
# If ssh-copy-id is missing, do it manually:
cat ~/.ssh/wfm_instance.pub | ssh adminprms98@101.50.84.209 \
  "mkdir -p ~/.ssh && chmod 700 ~/.ssh && cat >> ~/.ssh/authorized_keys && chmod 600 ~/.ssh/authorized_keys"
Then reconnect with the key (command A above) — no password needed.

C) Just use the password (always works if SSH password auth is enabled):

ssh adminprms98@101.50.84.209
Step 3 — Make it one word: ssh wfm (optional but recommended)
Add this to ~/.ssh/config:

Host wfm
    HostName 101.50.84.209
    User adminprms98
    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/wfm_instance
    IdentitiesOnly yes
Now you can just run:

ssh wfm
If the connection times out
Make sure port 22 (SSH) is allowed in the instance's Security Group / firewall in the NCP panel — same place the RDP note mentions port 3389. Without it, every SSH attempt will hang.

